  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About FD Interest Rates</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Which bank gives the highest FD interest rate in 2026?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Among major banks, IndusInd Bank and Kotak Mahindra Bank offer some of the highest FD rates (up to 7.50%). However, NBFCs like Bajaj Finance (up to 8.05%) and Shriram Finance (up to 7.95%) offer even higher rates. For senior citizens, Bajaj Finance FD offers the best rate at 8.30%. Small finance banks like Unity SFB and Utkarsh SFB also offer competitive rates above 8%.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Is FD interest income taxable?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, FD interest is fully taxable and added to your total income. TDS at 10% is deducted if annual interest exceeds ₹40,000 (₹50,000 for senior citizens). If your total income is below the taxable limit, submit Form 15G (or 15H for seniors) to avoid TDS. The total interest earned is taxed at your applicable income tax slab rate.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can I break an FD before maturity?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, most banks allow premature withdrawal of FDs with a penalty of 0.5%–1% on the applicable interest rate. Tax-saving 5-year FDs cannot be broken before maturity. Some banks now offer FDs with no premature withdrawal penalty for specific tenures. Consider a sweep-in FD or flexi-deposit for better liquidity without penalties.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the DICGC insurance limit for FDs?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>DICGC insures deposits up to ₹5 lakh per depositor per bank — this includes principal plus interest across all accounts (savings, FD, RD, current) in that bank. If you have ₹10 lakh to invest, consider splitting across two banks for full DICGC coverage. NBFC deposits are not covered by DICGC but are regulated by RBI.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the difference between cumulative and non-cumulative FD?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>In a cumulative FD, interest is compounded quarterly and paid at maturity — ideal for wealth building as you earn interest on interest. In a non-cumulative FD, interest is paid out at regular intervals (monthly/quarterly/annually) — ideal for regular income needs like retirees. The stated interest rate is the same, but cumulative FDs yield higher effective returns due to compounding.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

